task.summary: Default task
Added some basic skeleton constraints
Added Assert class
Added Contains class for list/string assertions
Remove IntelliJ comment
Rename satisfiedByObject to satisfiedBy, and add unimplemented generateFailureMessage method to Constraint
Implement generateFailureMessage method in subclasses
Use Number base class for numeric constraints and move Contains out of test (was acidental)
Add separate NumericEqualityConstraint so things like tolerances can be added for numeric equality constraints
Implement numeric equality and a tolerant numeric equality constraint. Also use overloading rather than reflection to decide whether to generate an ordinary equality constraint or a numeric one.
Added method to force a test to fail with an optional message
Refactor: move numeric constraints to sub-package
Add ComparisonConstraint and a skeletal LessThanConstraint
Change Assert.That to take a variable-length list of constraints, and add Constraint.withFailureMessage() to allow custom messages. Constraint is now an abstract class rather than an interface.
Add BetweenConstraint for checking whether a value lies between two bounds, and add method Is.between(lower, upper)
Add GreaterThanConstraint and Is.greaterThan()

Re-architect Constraint so the base class contains a boolean modifier (used for not-ing etc.) and uses the isSatisfiedBy method to delegate to subclass implementations of satisfiedBy and then apply the modifier.
Rename modifiers for clarity and move to sub-package
Added a load of simple constraints - Is.True/False, Is.Null, Is.NaN
Add ModifiedIs which allows access to Is methods but with a boolean modifier attached

Upon reconsideration, attaching boolean modifiers is a very bad idea. Instead, modification is done by constraints - for instance, InvertModifier is a constraint which contains the constraint to be inverted. Could use this to do similar things for or() and the like.

Upon reconsideration, attaching boolean modifiers is a very bad idea. Instead, modification is done by constraints - for instance, InvertModifier is a constraint which contains the constraint to be inverted. Could use this to do similar things for or() and the like.
Reimplement Is.not().whatever() with IsNot class (seems the only reasonable way of doing it at the moment, duplicative though it may be)
More consistency - use Is methods in all IsNot wrapper methods
Optimise imports
Add and/or modifiers and Constraint.and(Constraint), Constraint.or(Constraint) syntax
Implement failure message generation
Add base class for modifiers
Add reference equality constraint, and extra syntactic sugar in Is
Updated IsNot with new methods added to Is, and created a test ensuring IsNot contains all methods from Is
